nor, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","of Hamton Manor, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Hampton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: habitational name from any of numerous places called Hampton, including the cities of Southampton and Northampton (both of which were originally simply <i>Hamtun</i>). These all share the final Old English element <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’, but the first is variously <i>hām</i> ‘homestead’, <i>hamm</i> ‘water meadow’, or <i>hēan</i>, weak dative case (originally used after a preposition and article) of <i>hēah</i> ‘high’. This surname is also found in Ireland, having first been taken there in the medieval period.","History: The descendants of the clergyman Thomas Hampton, resident at Jamestown, VA, in 1630, lived in VA through three generations, multiplying their homesteads as the colony expanded and then branched into SC. This very common English name was brought independently to North America by many other bearers."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Stephen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Usual English spelling of the name of the first Christian martyr (Acts 6–7), whose feast is accordingly celebrated next after Christ's own (  26 December ). His name is derived from the Greek word <i>stephanos</i> ‘garland, crown’."],"variants":[{"name":"Stephan","meanings":["Variant of   Stephen  , preserving the vowels of the Greek name."]},{"name":"Steven","meanings":["Variant of   Stephen  , reflecting the normal pronunciation of the name in the English-speaking world."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":81,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":90,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Stephen de Hampton was born in Wolverhampton, Staffordshire, England as the son of William de Hampton. He married Mrs Stephen de Hampton about 1249, in Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1252, in his hometown."},"et":{"–1252":"–1252","–Female":"Surnud","1200–1243":"1200–1243","1250–1268":"1250–1268","1252–1317":"1252–1317","–1246":"–1246","1215":"1215","1246":"1246","1224":"1224","1268":"1268","1200":"1200","1243":"1243","about 1249":"umbes 1249","19 October 1250":"19. oktoober 1250","1252":"1252","1250":"1250","1317":"1317","Newport, Isle of Wight, England":"Newport, Isle of Wight, Hampshire, Inglismaa, Un